post_text:
Please join us in congratulating our student Jack Sands! A few weeks ago, the Air Force Band (the top tier performing concert band with the US Air Force) held an opportunity for musicians between the ages of 5 and 21. Anyone interested had to submit a video of themselves performing one part of a duet written for their instrument. If their video was selected, they would be paired with a member of the USAF Band who would then play the other part of the duet. Only 50 slots were open across the country.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VgE6vXf0ZNU&t=6s

shared_text:
Cape Elizabeth Police Department is in Cape Elizabeth, Maine.
January 31 at 2:16 PM · Cape Elizabeth, ME ·

This past Wednesday, several officers from the Cape Elizabeth Police Department were invited to serve lunch to students and staff at the high school. The occasion was School Resource Officer Galvan’s Mexican Fiesta. The menu included chicken, beef, veggies for a vegetarian option, rice, beans, taco shells, flour tortillas, and cookies that were prepared by Officer Galvan and John Holdridge’s advisory students. The event was so well received that the officers will be doing something similar at the middle school at the end of February!
#mainepolice #capeelizabeth #schoolresourceofficer #lunch #noms #yummy #police @ Cape Elizabeth, Maine

I'm sacrificing my pride (it's not a great picture of me) for these athletes who cheered each other on, encouraged one another, congratulated and stood in frigid temperatures to complete their first race at Shawnee Peak. The top individual spots were nabbed by Capers, both boys and girls, and the Girls' team tied in points with Fryeburg Academy. We were officially given the 2nd place spot. All in all, a fun night!

Thanks to the parent volunteers!

-Coach Jen

post_text:
Egypt Week!
This week the third grade students in Julie Merriam’s and Kate Zeller’s third grade classes engaged in an exciting study of Egypt, learning about scale and using multiplication squares as they built pyramids, comparing weather conditions in Cape Elizabeth and Cairo, building boats to test strengths and weaknesses, studying fashion as it relates to climate in ancient Egypt and present day Maine, and much more. The week culminated with a presentation of their work to parents and friends and an Egyptian funeral procession complete with the burying of each student’s sarcophagus in a pyramid.

post_text: On Tuesday, December 10, 2019 33 students travelled to the State House in Augusta to receive recognition for their art work that is currently being displayed in the Department of Education. The ceremony started with a message from Jason Anderson, the Visual and Performing Arts Specialist for the Maine Department of Education, followed by remarks from Dan Chuhta, Deputy Commissioner of Education. The student artists were individually recognized with certificates presented by Senator Rebecca Millett and William Hess, Chair of the State Board of Education. A letter from Governor Mills was read and presented to each student. Following the ceremony the group was escorted through the Department of Education to see the 42 Cape Elizabeth student pieces works that are on display.

post_text:
Naturalization Ceremony, December 6, 2019:
This morning, through the efforts of Ted Jordan and Jeff Shedd, Cape Elizabeth High School hosted a Naturalization Ceremony during which over forty new citizens, from over 20 different countries became new citizens of the United States of America. The event was introduced by former Cape Elizabeth High School student, Hillary Saucier who now serves as an Immigration Services Officer for the U.S. Citizenship and Immigration Services. Keynote speakers were CEHS teachers Sonia Medina and Aysun Simpson. The Cape Elizabeth High School Wind Ensemble played the National Anthem for the ceremony and the Cape Elizabeth High School Chorus sang Give Us Your Tired, Your Poor. Congratulations and best wishes to our new citizens!

MEDIA ADVISORY: Maine DOE to Host Student Arts Showcase Celebration 12/10 at Maine State House

Maine Department of Education
December 5, 2019 at 4:51 PM ·

The Maine Department of Education (DOE) is pleased to invite the media to attend a celebration of the Maine Arts Showcase, where the selected artwork of 42 young artists from Cape Elizabeth Middle School will be recognized. Since October, these students’ work has been on exhibit throughout the Maine DOE, where it will remain until February 2020. The Arts Showcase is a long standing tradition of the Maine DOE where artwork of students from all over the state is showcased at the Department in a series of exhibits that happen throughout the year. On Tuesday night, the students in Mr. Kerr's 8th grade class participated in a Celebration of Learning where they presented their projects to family and community members. Natalie and Eliza compared two models of mussel farming, sock culture and raft culture, studying the benefits and limitations of each. They collected information for people who are interested in starting a mussel farming project.
#learning #aquaculture

Maine Department of Education
September 26, 2019 at 4:14 PM ·

The U.S. Department of Education today announced three Maine schools as National Blue Ribbon Schools for 2019. The recognition is based on a school’s overall academic performance or progress in closing achievement gaps among student subgroups.
